<div id="review_670670348" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/670670348" />
    <a title="Ingrid Hall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16107197-ingrid-hall"><img alt="Ingrid Hall" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442895363p2/16107197.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/670670348?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ingrid Hall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ingrid Hall" href="/user/show/16107197-ingrid-hall">Ingrid Hall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer670670348" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8652968504413288768">Adversity Builds Character - An inspirational true life story of disability, addiction and acceptance.<br/><br/>Tom Ufert, a 46-year-old quadriplegic afflicted with three different disabilities describes himself as &quot;an inspirational voice in our troubled times.&quot; He has worked tirelessly as a campaigner for numerous AIDS charities and currently lives in Florida.<br/><br/>I have been very interested in reviewing this book ever since I had the pleasure of interviewing Tom recently as it was clear from talking to him t</span>
  <span id="freeText8652968504413288768" style="display:none">Adversity Builds Character - An inspirational true life story of disability, addiction and acceptance.<br /><br />Tom Ufert, a 46-year-old quadriplegic afflicted with three different disabilities describes himself as "an inspirational voice in our troubled times." He has worked tirelessly as a campaigner for numerous AIDS charities and currently lives in Florida.<br /><br />I have been very interested in reviewing this book ever since I had the pleasure of interviewing Tom recently as it was clear from talking to him that he had faced and indeed was still facing enormous challenges in his life. Indeed I was impressed by his strength of character, his resilience and his ability to keep putting one foot in front of the other in blatant defiance of the spiky curve balls being continually been hurled his way.<br /><br />An early quote "Rising up through trials and tribulations" alongside a colourful image of a phoenix, perfectly sums the author up and sets the tone for what is to come. The book opens proper with the author's life changing accident and is written in such an engaging, accessible and slightly self deprecating style that you can't help but be hooked. Each chapter starts with a punch and the drama is perfectly timed to make you want to keep reading. His childhood is recalled colourfully and I found myself roaring with laughter as I read about the mutual animosity between his father and the family cat, the wonderfully named "Madam Queen" and the cat pooing on his father's side of the bed...<br /><br />The author has clearly faced many struggles...Some of which a lot of people the world over will have experience of and some more extreme and you are at times left wondering just how one person can experience so much and still function as a human being. There are no apparent limits or boundaries to what the author is willing to discuss and everything from his mother's illness, the fallout from his own catastrophic injuries to issues such as HIV and sexual abuse are discussed and recalled in a no frills/no holding back kind of way which I found both thought provoking and refreshing. His belief in and love of God is apparent and whilst sometimes I would be turned off by that in a book, on this occasion I felt that his belief is so strong that it can only be good.<br /><br />My only concern with the book is the cost, particularly of the kindle edition because with such a plethora of survivor/real life stories out there to choose from, I am not sure if anyone coming across it for the first time would take a punt on it and my one piece of advice to him would be to consider lowering the cost. That said, Tom Ufert's recollection of his own personal experiences and struggles is powerful, compelling and extremely moving and is well worth a read.<br /><br />I am offering free interviews and reviews for indie authors find out more at <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.ingridhall.com">www.ingridhall.com</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="8652968504413288768" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


